# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: typer-cli
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] A command-line option or simply option (also known as a flag or switch) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Many languages offer functionality for argument parsing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, the C POSIX library provides getopt(), Python offers a module called `argparse`, while C# provides a namespace `System.CommandLine`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In others, they are not bundled in the standard library, but rather must be used through third-party libraries.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In many languages, particularly C-derived languages, arguments are accessed through the parameters of the `main()` method.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] For example, in C and C++, the `main` method has signature `int main(int argc, char* argv[]);`, where `argc` is the number of arguments plus the name of the program, and `argv` is an array of C-strings where `argv[0]` is the name of the program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] In Java and C#, the `main()` method instead takes one parameter `args` of type `String[]` (an array of strings).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Meanwhile, in some other languages, such as Rust, command-line arguments are accessed by a method `std::env::args()`, allowing a global point of access rather than having to be obtained from `main()`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C uses `argv` to process command-line arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C POSIX library also has functions called `getopt()` and `getopt_long()`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C++ accesses arguments the same way as C.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The POCO C++ Libraries offer a class `Poco::Util::OptionProcessor` for parsing command-line arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Boost provides a class `boost::program_options::command_line_parser`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Meanwhile, Google has a library called `gflags`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also a `argparse` library for C++17+ offers a similar API for argument parsing to Python `argparse`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] C# provides the `System.CommandLine` namespace for advanced command-line argument parsing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The D programming language provides a module `std.getopt`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Go provides the `flag` package for argument parsing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Haskell provides the library `System.Console.GetOpt`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] The Apache Commons library `org.apache.commons.cli` provides command-line argument parsing capabilities.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also the `gnu.getopt` library, ported from GNU getopt.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] There is also `Getopt::Long` and `Getopt::Std` for argument parsing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] PHP uses `argc` as a count of arguments and `argv` as an array containing the values of the arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Python also has a module called `argparse` in the standard library for parsing command-line arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Racket uses a `current-command-line-arguments` parameter, and provides a `racket/cmdline` library for parsing these arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Rather than being part of the parameters of `main()` (like other C-style languages), in Rust the args are in `std::env::args()`, which returns a `std::env::Args` and is converted to a `Vec<String>` with `.collect()`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] A popular Rust library for command-line argument parsing is `clap`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript programs written for Node.js use the `process.argv` global variable.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] Node.js programs are invoked by running the interpreter node interpreter with a given file, so the first two arguments will be `node` and the name of the JavaScript source file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] It is often useful to extract the rest of the arguments by slicing a sub-array from `process.argv`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript written for Bun use `Bun.argv` and the `util.parseArgs` function.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-argument-parsing] JavaScript written for Deno use `Deno.args` and the `parseArgs` function.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:typer-cli/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:typer-cli/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] Learn how to use **Typer** in this step-by-step **Tutorial** - **User Guide**.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] It covers everything you need to know from the **simplest scripts** to **complex CLI applications**.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] If you need a refresher about how to use Python type hints, check the first part of FastAPI's Python types intro.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] You can also check the mypy cheat sheet.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] These type hints are what give you autocomplete in your editor and several other features.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] This tutorial shows you how to use **Typer** with all its features, step by step.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] Each section gradually builds on the previous ones, but it's structured to separate topics, so that you can go directly to any specific one to solve your specific CLI needs.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] It is also built to work as a future reference so you can come back and see exactly what you need.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] All the code blocks can be copied and used directly (they are tested Python files).
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] It is **HIGHLY encouraged** that you write or copy the code, edit it and run it locally.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] Using it in your editor is what really shows you the benefits of **Typer**, seeing how little code you have to write, all the **inline errors**, **autocompletion**, etc.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] And running the examples is what will really help you **understand** what is going on.
[src:typer-cli/tutorial] You can learn a lot more by **running some examples** and **playing around** with them than by reading all the docs here.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:typer-cli/type-hint] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The object of use can be a software application, website, book, tool, machine, process, vehicle, or anything a human interacts with.
[src:typer-cli/usability] A usability study may be conducted as a primary job function by a *usability analyst* or as a secondary job function by designers, technical writers, marketing personnel, and others.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is widely used in consumer electronics, communication, and knowledge transfer objects (such as a cookbook, a document or online help) and mechanical objects such as a door handle or a hammer.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability includes methods of measuring usability, such as needs analysis and the study of the principles behind an object's perceived efficiency or elegance.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In human-computer interaction and computer science, usability studies the elegance and clarity with which the interaction with a computer program or a web site (web usability) is designed.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability considers user satisfaction and utility as quality components, and aims to improve user experience through iterative design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Complex computer systems find their way into everyday life, and at the same time the market is saturated with competing brands.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This has made usability more popular and widely recognized in recent years, as companies see the benefits of researching and developing their products with user-oriented methods instead of technology-oriented methods.
[src:typer-cli/usability] By understanding and researching the interaction between product and user, the *usability expert* can also provide insight that is unattainable by traditional company-oriented market research.
[src:typer-cli/usability] For example, after observing and interviewing users, the usability expert may identify needed functionality or design flaws that were not anticipated.
[src:typer-cli/usability] A method called *contextual inquiry* does this in the naturally occurring context of the users own environment.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In the user-centered design paradigm, the product is designed with its intended users in mind at all times.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In the user-driven or participatory design paradigm, some of the users become actual or de facto members of the design team.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The term *user friendly* is often used as a synonym for *usable*, though it may also refer to accessibility.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability describes the quality of user experience across websites, software, products, and environments.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There is no consensus about the relation of the terms ergonomics (or human factors) and usability.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Some think of usability as the software specialization of the larger topic of ergonomics.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Others view these topics as tangential, with ergonomics focusing on physiological matters (e.g., turning a door handle) and usability focusing on psychological matters (e.g., recognizing that a door can be opened by turning its handle).
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability is also important in website development (web usability).
[src:typer-cli/usability] According to Jakob Nielsen, "Studies of user behavior on the Web find a low tolerance for difficult designs or slow sites.
[src:typer-cli/usability] And they don't want to learn how to use a home page.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There's no such thing as a training class or a manual for a Web site.
[src:typer-cli/usability] People have to be able to grasp the functioning of the site immediately after scanning the home page—for a few seconds at most." Otherwise, most casual users simply leave the site and browse or shop elsewhere.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability can also include the concept of prototypicality, which is how much a particular thing conforms to the expected shared norm, for instance, in website design, users prefer sites that conform to recognised design norms.
[src:typer-cli/usability] ISO defines usability as "The extent to which a product can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction in a specified context of use." The word "usability" also refers to methods for improving ease-of-use during the design process.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability is often associated with the functionalities of the product (cf.
[src:typer-cli/usability] ISO definition, below), in addition to being solely a characteristic of the user interface (cf. framework of system acceptability, also below, which separates *usefulness* into *usability* and *utility*).
[src:typer-cli/usability] For example, in the context of mainstream consumer products, an automobile lacking a reverse gear could be considered *unusable* according to the former view, and *lacking in utility* according to the latter view.
[src:typer-cli/usability] When evaluating user interfaces for usability, the definition can be as simple as "the perception of a target user of the effectiveness (fit for purpose) and efficiency (work or time required to use) of the Interface".
[src:typer-cli/usability] Each component may be measured subjectively against criteria, e.g., Principles of User Interface Design, to provide a metric, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is important to distinguish between usability testing and usability engineering.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability testing is the measurement of ease of use of a product or piece of software.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In contrast, usability engineering (UE) is the research and design process that ensures a product with good usability.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability is a non-functional requirement.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As with other non-functional requirements, usability cannot be directly measured but must be quantified by means of indirect measures or attributes such as, for example, the number of reported problems with ease-of-use of a system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The term intuitive is often listed as a desirable trait in usable interfaces, sometimes used as a synonym for learnable.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In the past, Jef Raskin discouraged using this term in user interface design, claiming that easy to use interfaces are often easy because of the user's exposure to previous similar systems, thus the term 'familiar' should be preferred.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As an example: Two vertical lines "||" on media player buttons do not intuitively mean "pause"—they do so by convention.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Researchers have also investigated intuitive interaction for older people, people living with dementia, and children.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Some have argued that aiming for "intuitive" interfaces (based on reusing existing skills with interaction systems) could lead designers to discard a better design solution only because it would require a novel approach and to stick with boring designs.
[src:typer-cli/usability] However, applying familiar features into a new interface has been shown not to result in boring design if designers use creative approaches rather than simple copying.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The throwaway remark that "the only intuitive interface is the nipple; everything else is learned." is still occasionally mentioned.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Any breastfeeding mother or lactation consultant will tell you this is inaccurate and the nipple does in fact require learning on both sides.
[src:typer-cli/usability] However, the term intuitive interaction has become well accepted in the research community over the past 20 or so years and, although not perfect, it should probably be accepted and used.
[src:typer-cli/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 ("Ergonomics of human-system interaction—Usability methods supporting human-centered design") is an International Standards Organization (ISO) standard that provides information on human-centered usability methods that can be used for design and evaluation.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It details the advantages, disadvantages, and other factors relevant to using each usability method.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It explains the implications of the stage of the life cycle and the individual project characteristics for the selection of usability methods and provides examples of usability methods in context.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The main users of ISO/TR 16982:2002 are project managers.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It therefore addresses technical human factors and ergonomics issues only to the extent necessary to allow managers to understand their relevance and importance in the design process as a whole.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The guidance in ISO/TR 16982:2002 can be tailored for specific design situations by using the lists of issues characterizing the context of use of the product to be delivered.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Selection of appropriate usability methods should also take account of the relevant life-cycle process.
[src:typer-cli/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 is restricted to methods that are widely used by usability specialists and project managers.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It does *not* specify the details of how to implement or carry out the usability methods described.
[src:typer-cli/usability] ISO 9241 is a multi-part standard that covers a number of aspects of people working with computers.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Although originally titled *Ergonomic requirements for office work with visual display terminals (VDTs)*, it has been retitled to the more generic *Ergonomics of Human System Interaction*.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As part of this change, ISO is renumbering some parts of the standard so that it can cover more topics, e.g. tactile and haptic interaction.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The first part to be renumbered was part 10 in 2006, now part 110.
[src:typer-cli/usability] IEC 62366-1:2015 + COR1:2016 & IEC/TR 62366-2 provide guidance on usability engineering specific to a medical device.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Any system or device designed for use by people should be easy to use, easy to learn, easy to remember (the instructions), and helpful to users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The design team should be user-driven and it should be in direct contact with potential users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Several evaluation methods, including personas, cognitive modeling, inspection, inquiry, prototyping, and testing methods may contribute to understanding potential users and their perceptions of how well the product or process works.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability considerations, such as who the users are and their experience with similar systems must be examined.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As part of understanding users, this knowledge must "...be played against the tasks that the users will be expected to perform." This includes the analysis of what tasks the users will perform, which are most important, and what decisions the users will make while using your system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Designers must understand how cognitive and emotional characteristics of users will relate to a proposed system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] One way to stress the importance of these issues in the designers' minds is to use personas, which are made-up representative users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] See below for further discussion of personas.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Another more expensive but more insightful method is to have a panel of potential users work closely with the design team from the early stages.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Test the system early on, and test the system on real users using behavioral measurements.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This includes testing the system for both learnability and usability.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is important in this stage to use quantitative usability specifications such as time and errors to complete tasks and number of users to test, as well as examine performance and attitudes of the users testing the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Finally, "reviewing or demonstrating" a system before the user tests it can result in misleading results.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The emphasis of empirical measurement is on measurement, both informal and formal, which can be carried out through a variety of evaluation methods.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Iterative design is a design methodology based on a cyclic process of prototyping, testing, analyzing, and refining a product or process.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Based on the results of testing the most recent iteration of a design, changes and refinements are made.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This process is intended to ultimately improve the quality and functionality of a design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In iterative design, interaction with the designed system is used as a form of research for informing and evolving a project, as successive versions, or iterations of a design are implemented.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The key requirements for Iterative Design are: identification of required changes, an ability to make changes, and a willingness to make changes.
[src:typer-cli/usability] When a problem is encountered, there is no set method to determine the correct solution.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Rather, there are empirical methods that can be used during system development or after the system is delivered, usually a more inopportune time.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Ultimately, iterative design works towards meeting goals such as making the system user friendly, easy to use, easy to operate, simple, etc.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There are a variety of usability evaluation methods.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Certain methods use data from users, while others rely on usability experts.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There are usability evaluation methods for all stages of design and development, from product definition to final design modifications.
[src:typer-cli/usability] When choosing a method, consider cost, time constraints, and appropriateness.
[src:typer-cli/usability] For a brief overview of methods, see Comparison of usability evaluation methods or continue reading below.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability methods can be further classified into the subcategories below.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Cognitive modeling involves creating a computational model to estimate how long it takes people to perform a given task.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Models are based on psychological principles and experimental studies to determine times for cognitive processing and motor movements.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Cognitive models can be used to improve user interfaces or predict problem errors and pitfalls during the design process.
[src:typer-cli/usability] With parallel design, several people create an initial design from the same set of requirements.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Each person works independently, and when finished, shares concepts with the group.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The design team considers each solution, and each designer uses the best ideas to further improve their own solution.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This process helps generate many different, diverse ideas, and ensures that the best ideas from each design are integrated into the final concept.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This process can be repeated several times until the team is satisfied with the final concept.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Sometimes it is useful to break a task down and analyze each individual aspect separately.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This helps the tester locate specific areas for improvement.
[src:typer-cli/usability] To do this, it is necessary to understand how the human brain processes information.
[src:typer-cli/usability] A model of the human processor is shown below.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Many studies have been done to estimate the cycle times, decay times, and capacities of each of these processors.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Variables that affect these can include subject age, aptitudes, ability, and the surrounding environment.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Long-term memory is believed to have an infinite capacity and decay time.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Keystroke level modeling is essentially a less comprehensive version of GOMS that makes simplifying assumptions in order to reduce calculation time and complexity.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve observation of users by an experimenter, or the testing and evaluation of a program by an expert reviewer.
[src:typer-cli/usability] They provide more quantitative data as tasks can be timed and recorded.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Card sorting is a way to involve users in grouping information for a website's usability review.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Participants in a card sorting session are asked to organize the content from a Web site in a way that makes sense to them.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Participants review items from a Web site and then group these items into categories.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Card sorting helps to learn how users think about the content and how they would organize the information on the Web site.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Card sorting helps to build the structure for a Web site, decide what to put on the home page, and label the home page categories.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It also helps to ensure that information is organized on the site in a way that is logical to users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Tree testing is a way to evaluate the effectiveness of a website's top-down organization.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Participants are given "find it" tasks, then asked to drill down through successive text lists of topics and subtopics to find a suitable answer.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Tree testing evaluates the findability and labeling of topics in a site, separate from its navigation controls or visual design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Ethnographic analysis is derived from anthropology.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Field observations are taken at a site of a possible user, which track the artifacts of work such as Post-It notes, items on desktop, shortcuts, and items in trash bins.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These observations also gather the sequence of work and interruptions that determine the user's typical day.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Heuristic evaluation is a usability engineering method for finding and assessing usability problems in a user interface design as part of an iterative design process.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It involves having a small set of evaluators examining the interface and using recognized usability principles (the "heuristics").
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is the most popular of the usability inspection methods, as it is quick, cheap, and easy.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Heuristic evaluation was developed to aid in the design of computer user-interface design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It relies on expert reviewers to discover usability problems and then categorize and rate them by a set of principles (heuristics.) It is widely used based on its speed and cost-effectiveness.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Jakob Nielsen's list of ten heuristics is the most commonly used in industry.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These are ten general principles for user interface design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] They are called "heuristics" because they are more in the nature of rules of thumb than specific usability guidelines.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Thus, by determining which guidelines are violated, the usability of a device can be determined.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability inspection is a review of a system based on a set of guidelines.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The review is conducted by a group of experts who are deeply familiar with the concepts of usability in design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The experts focus on a list of areas in design that have been shown to be troublesome for users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Pluralistic Inspections are meetings where users, developers, and human factors people meet together to discuss and evaluate step by step of a task scenario.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As more people inspect the scenario for problems, the higher the probability to find problems.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In addition, the more interaction in the team, the faster the usability issues are resolved.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In consistency inspection, expert designers review products or projects to ensure consistency across multiple products to look if it does things in the same way as their own designs.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Activity analysis is a usability method used in preliminary stages of development to get a sense of situation.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It involves an investigator observing users as they work in the field.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Also referred to as user observation, it is useful for specifying user requirements and studying currently used tasks and subtasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The data collected are qualitative and useful for defining the problem.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The following usability evaluation methods involve collecting qualitative data from users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Although the data collected is subjective, it provides valuable information on what the user wants.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Task analysis means learning about users' goals and users' ways of working.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Task analysis can also mean figuring out what more specific tasks users must do to meet those goals and what steps they must take to accomplish those tasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Along with user and task analysis, a third analysis is often used: understanding users' environments (physical, social, cultural, and technological environments).
[src:typer-cli/usability] A focus group is a focused discussion where a moderator leads a group of participants through a set of questions on a particular topic.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Although typically used as a marketing tool, focus groups are sometimes used to evaluate usability.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Used in the product definition stage, a group of 6 to 10 users are gathered to discuss what they desire in a product.
[src:typer-cli/usability] An experienced focus group facilitator is hired to guide the discussion to areas of interest for the developers.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Focus groups are typically videotaped to help get verbatim quotes, and clips are often used to summarize opinions.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The data gathered is not usually quantitative, but can help get an idea of a target group's opinion.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Surveys have the advantages of being inexpensive, require no testing equipment, and results reflect the users' opinions.
[src:typer-cli/usability] When written carefully and given to actual users who have experience with the product and knowledge of design, surveys provide useful feedback on the strong and weak areas of the usability of a design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This is a very common method and often does not appear to be a survey, but just a warranty card.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is often very difficult for designers to conduct usability tests with the exact system being designed.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Cost constraints, size, and design constraints usually lead the designer to creating a prototype of the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Instead of creating the complete final system, the designer may test different sections of the system, thus making several small models of each component of the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Prototyping is an attitude and an output, as it is a process for generating and reflecting on tangible ideas by allowing failure to occur early. prototyping helps people to see what could be of communicating a shared vision, and of giving shape to the future.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The types of usability prototypes may vary from using paper models, index cards, hand drawn models, or storyboards.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This tool kit is a wide library of methods that used the traditional programming language and it is primarily developed for computer programmers.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The code created for testing in the tool kit approach can be used in the final product.
[src:typer-cli/usability] However, to get the highest benefit from the tool, the user must be an expert programmer.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The two elements of this approach include a parts library and a method used for identifying the connection between the parts.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This approach can be used by almost anyone and it is a great asset for designers with repetitive tasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This approach is a combination of the tool kit approach and the part kit approach.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Both the dialogue designers and the programmers are able to interact with this prototyping tool.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Rapid prototyping is a method used in early stages of development to validate and refine the usability of a system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It can be used to quickly and cheaply evaluate user-interface designs without the need for an expensive working model.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This can help remove hesitation to change the design, since it is implemented before any real programming begins.
[src:typer-cli/usability] One such method of rapid prototyping is paper prototyping.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve testing of subjects for the most quantitative data.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usually recorded on video, they provide task completion time and allow for observation of attitude.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Regardless to how carefully a system is designed, all theories must be tested using usability tests.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability tests involve typical users using the system (or product) in a realistic environment [see simulation].
[src:typer-cli/usability] Observation of the user's behavior, emotions, and difficulties while performing different tasks, often identify areas of improvement for the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] While conducting usability tests, designers must use usability metrics to identify what it is they are going to measure, or the usability metrics.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These metrics are often variable, and change in conjunction with the scope and goals of the project.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The number of subjects being tested can also affect usability metrics, as it is often easier to focus on specific demographics.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Qualitative design phases, such as general usability (can the task be accomplished?), and user satisfaction are also typically done with smaller groups of subjects.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Using inexpensive prototypes on small user groups provides more detailed information, because of the more interactive atmosphere, and the designer's ability to focus more on the individual user.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As the designs become more complex, the testing must become more formalized.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Testing equipment will become more sophisticated and testing metrics become more quantitative.
[src:typer-cli/usability] With a more refined prototype, designers often test effectiveness, efficiency, and subjective satisfaction, by asking the user to complete various tasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These categories are measured by the percent that complete the task, how long it takes to complete the tasks, ratios of success to failure to complete the task, time spent on errors, the number of errors, rating scale of satisfactions, number of times user seems frustrated, etc.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Additional observations of the users give designers insight on navigation difficulties, controls, conceptual models, etc.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The ultimate goal of analyzing these metrics is to find/create a prototype design that users like and use to successfully perform given tasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] After conducting usability tests, it is important for a designer to record what was observed, in addition to why such behavior occurred and modify the model according to the results.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Often it is quite difficult to distinguish the source of the design errors, and what the user did wrong.
[src:typer-cli/usability] However, effective usability tests will not generate a solution to the problems, but provide modified design guidelines for continued testing.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Additionally, this style of user testing also provides an opportunity to segment feedback by demographic, attitudinal and behavioral type.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The tests are carried out in the user's own environment (rather than labs) helping further simulate real-life scenario testing.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This approach also provides a vehicle to easily solicit feedback from users in remote areas.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There are two types, quantitative or qualitative.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Quantitative use large sample sized and task based surveys.
[src:typer-cli/usability] These types of studies are useful for validating suspected usability issues.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Qualitative studies are best used as exploratory research, in small sample sizes but frequent, even daily iterations.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The growth in mobile and associated platforms and services (e.g.: Mobile gaming has experienced 20x growth in 2010–2012) has generated a need for unmoderated remote usability testing on mobile devices, both for websites but especially for app interactions.
[src:typer-cli/usability] One methodology consists of shipping cameras and special camera holding fixtures to dedicated testers, and having them record the screens of the mobile smart-phone or tablet device, usually using an HD camera.
[src:typer-cli/usability] A drawback of this approach is that the finger movements of the respondent can obscure the view of the screen, in addition to the bias and logistical issues inherent in shipping special hardware to selected respondents.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The Think aloud protocol is a method of gathering data that is used in both usability and psychology studies.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It involves getting a user to verbalize their thought processes (i.e. expressing their opinions, thoughts, anticipations, and actions) as they perform a task or set of tasks.
[src:typer-cli/usability] As a widespread method of usability testing, think aloud provides the researchers with the ability to discover what user really think during task performance and completion.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Often an instructor is present to prompt the user into being more vocal as they work.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Similar to the Subjects-in-Tandem method, it is useful in pinpointing problems and is relatively simple to set up.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Additionally, it can provide insight into the user's attitude, which can not usually be discerned from a survey or questionnaire.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Rapid Iterative Testing and Evaluation (RITE) is an iterative usability method similar to traditional "discount" usability testing.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The tester and team must define a target population for testing, schedule participants to come into the lab, decide on how the users behaviors will be measured, construct a test script and have participants engage in a verbal protocol (e.g., think aloud).
[src:typer-cli/usability] However it differs from these methods in that it advocates that changes to the user interface are made as soon as a problem is identified and a solution is clear.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Sometimes this can occur after observing as few as 1 participant.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Once the data for a participant has been collected the usability engineer and team decide if they will be making any changes to the prototype prior to the next participant.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The changed interface is then tested with the remaining users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Subjects-in-tandem (also called co-discovery) is the pairing of subjects in a usability test to gather important information on the ease of use of a product.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Subjects tend to discuss the tasks they have to accomplish out loud and through these discussions observers learn where the problem areas of a design are.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Component-based usability testing is an approach which aims to test the usability of elementary units of an interaction system, referred to as interaction components.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The approach includes component-specific quantitative measures based on user interaction recorded in log files, and component-based usability questionnaires.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is a method of evaluating the user interaction of a working prototype or final product.
[src:typer-cli/usability] It is used to evaluate the system's ease of learning.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is useful to understand the user's thought processes and decision making when interacting with a system, specially for first-time or infrequent users.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Benchmarking creates standardized test materials for a specific type of design.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Four key characteristics are considered when establishing a benchmark: time to do the core task, time to fix errors, time to learn applications, and the functionality of the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Once there is a benchmark, other designs can be compared to it to determine the usability of the system.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Many of the common objectives of usability studies, such as trying to understand user behavior or exploring alternative designs, must be put aside.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Unlike many other usability methods or types of labs studies, benchmark studies more closely resemble true experimental psychology lab studies, with greater attention to detail on methodology, study protocol and data analysis.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Meta-analysis is a statistical procedure to combine results across studies to integrate the findings.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This phrase was coined in 1976 as a quantitative literature review.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This type of evaluation is very powerful for determining the usability of a device because it combines multiple studies to provide very accurate quantitative support.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Personas are fictitious characters created to represent a site or product's different user types and their associated demographics and technographics.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Alan Cooper introduced the concept of using personas as a part of interactive design in 1998 in his book *The Inmates Are Running the Asylum*, but had used this concept since as early as 1975.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Personas are a usability evaluation method that can be used at various design stages.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The most typical time to create personas is at the beginning of designing so that designers have a tangible idea of who the users of their product will be.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Personas are the archetypes that represent actual groups of users and their needs, which can be a general description of person, context, or usage scenario.
[src:typer-cli/usability] This technique turns marketing data on target user population into a few physical concepts of users to create empathy among the design team, with the final aim of tailoring a product more closely to how the personas will use it.
[src:typer-cli/usability] To gather the marketing data that personas require, several tools can be used, including online surveys, web analytics, customer feedback forms, and usability tests, and interviews with customer-service representatives.
[src:typer-cli/usability] An increase in usability generally positively affects several facets of a company's output quality.
[src:typer-cli/usability] By working to improve said factors, corporations can achieve their goals of increased output at lower costs, while potentially creating optimal levels of customer satisfaction.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There are numerous reasons why each of these factors correlates to overall improvement.
[src:typer-cli/usability] For example, making software user interfaces easier to understand reduces the need for extensive training.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The improved interface tends to lower the time needed to perform tasks, and so would both raise the productivity levels for employees and reduce development time (and thus costs).
[src:typer-cli/usability] Each of the aforementioned factors are not mutually exclusive; rather they should be understood to work in conjunction to form the overall workplace environment.
[src:typer-cli/usability] In the 2010s, usability is recognized as an important software quality attribute, earning its place among more traditional attributes such as performance, robustness and aesthetic appearance.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Various academic programs focus on usability.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Several usability consultancy companies have emerged, and traditional consultancy and design firms offer similar services.
[src:typer-cli/usability] There is some resistance to integrating usability work in organisations.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability is seen as a vague concept, it is difficult to measure and other areas are prioritised when IT projects run out of time or money.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Usability practitioners are sometimes trained as industrial engineers, psychologists, kinesiologists, systems design engineers, or with a degree in information architecture, information or library science, or Human-Computer Interaction (HCI).
[src:typer-cli/usability] More often though they are people who are trained in specific applied fields who have taken on a usability focus within their organization.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Anyone who aims to make tools easier to use and more effective for their desired function within the context of work or everyday living can benefit from studying usability principles and guidelines.
[src:typer-cli/usability] For those seeking to extend their training, the User Experience Professionals' Association offers online resources, reference lists, courses, conferences, and local chapter meetings.
[src:typer-cli/usability] The UXPA also sponsors World Usability Day each November.
[src:typer-cli/usability] Related professional organizations include the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society (HFES) and the Association for Computing Machinery's special interest groups in Computer Human Interaction (SIGCHI), Design of Communication (SIGDOC) and Computer Graphics and Interactive Techniques (SIGGRAPH).
[src:typer-cli/usability] The Society for Technical Communication also has a special interest group on Usability and User Experience (UUX).
[src:typer-cli/usability] They publish a quarterly newsletter called *Usability Interface*.
